We equate the diagonal entries, obtaining $(a + 2c)a = 2a + 4b$. After distributing and rearranging terms, we arrive at the equation $a^2 - 2a = 4b - 2c.$ Equating the remaining diagonal entries as well, $3a + 4c = c + 3d$ reduces to $d = 2a + c.$ Combining these expressions for $a$ and $d$, we express $\frac{a - d}{c - 3b}$ as follows: $$
\frac{a - d}{c - 3b} \color{red}{= \frac{a - 2a - c}{c - 3b} = \frac{- a - c}{c - 3b}} = \frac{-(c + 3b)}{c - 3b} = \boxed{-1}.$$</answer>

 Since the matrices (\mathbf{A} and \mathbf{B}) are bound to commute, (\mathbf{B} can be any matrix whose determinant is zero.) In particular, we can make $\mathbf{B}$ singular (while equaling $\mathbf{A}$ in the off-diagonal positions.) We have, then, \begin{align*}
\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B} &= \mathbf{B}\mathbf{A} 
\\ \begin{pmatrix} 
